\begin_layout Standard
In the passage above, Marx identifies important changes in the London's
 housing-construction system during the first half of the nineteenth century.
 With his typically astute powers of observation, he highlights characteristics
 of the nascent system that today are familiar and in many countries have
 become dominant and defining features in the production of the built environmen
t, not only in housing construction but also in construction for commercial
 and other uses as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even more significant, this passage is the 
\emph on
only
\emph default
 place in all of Volume II of 
\emph on
Capital
\emph default
 where Marx gives land-rent a distinctive role in the circulation of capital.
 As the volume's subtitle suggests, it is about 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the process of circulation of capital.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 If land-rent is absent, this would imply that Marx deemed it largely tangential
 to the circulation of capital.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Indeed, elsewhere in the volume, Marx either treats land-rent as incidental
 or he explicitly rejects its relevance because it is only part of total
 surplus value.
 Thus, he uses land-rent as an example of the kind of fixed, short-term
 obligations that capitalists in industries with unavoidably long working
 periods, such as seasonal agriculture, must devise ways to cover while
 awaiting sale of their products 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand nocite
key "marx1967capital"

\end_inset

(p.
 235).
 When he considers how capitalists realize surplus value in the form of
 a greater sum of money than what they originally advanced, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "marx1967capital"

\end_inset

 (pp.
 333-4) dismisses land-rent's relevance:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\SpecialChar ldots
 there are only two points of departure: the capitalist and the 
\lang british
labourer
\lang american
.
 All third categories of persons must either receive money for their services
 from these two classes or, to the extent that they receive it without any
 services in return, they are joint owners of the surplus-value in the form
 of rent, interest, etc.
 That the surplus value does not all stay in the pocket of the industrial
 capitalist but must be shared by him with other persons, has nothing to
 do with the present question.
 The question is how he turns his surplus-value into money, not how the
 proceeds are later divided.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Chapter 19 reviews previous work of others and makes frequent reference
 to land-rent.
 But most such references are either quotations from the original sources
 or Marx's own comments about the sources in which he uses the term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ground-rent
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

