 He criticizes these sources, and his criticisms often maintain that ground-rent
 is a distraction when considering the circulation of capital, sometimes
 even merging it with the profit of industrial capital.
 For example, when discussing Adam Smith's treatment of circulating capital
 Marx notes that the circulating value has three parts: value of means of
 production, value of labor-power, and a portion that is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

source of 
\emph on
profits, including ground-rent
\emph default
, of the industrial capitalists \SpecialChar ldots

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

; he goes on to point out the value of means of production includes the
 revenues of actors engaged in their production, including 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

profits and 
\emph on
ground-rents for the capitalists
\emph default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

