\begin_layout Standard
The passage appears in a chapter devoted to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The Working Period
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: the time capital is tied up during a commodity's production (Chapter 12).
 Immediately before the passage, Marx makes the points that, other things
 being equal, longer working periods tie up more capital, as do production
 processes involving larger capital investments.
 Therefore, production of such things is not done capitalistically (i.e.,
 for profit by sale in the market) until capitalism is sufficiently developed,
 with capital highly concentrated in large firms and a mature credit system
 in place.
 To support this, he then uses house-building as an example.
 To be competitive, builders must be large-scale and build speculatively.
 Even so, the profit is insufficient to justify the capitalist builder's
 investment unless the credit system allows the capitalist to externalize
 risk and 
\emph on
land-rent augments profit
\emph default
 sufficiently to achieve a competitive return on investment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
