\begin_layout Standard
The passage from Marx quoted above describes an important change in the
 system for creating the built environment under capitalism.
 In the early nineteenth century, house-building was small scale; builders
 primarily worked directly for home buyers; those who could afford to purchase
 houses paid for the house in installments, and the payments came from their
 saved revenue; buyers owned the land before building began, and builders
 started building only if they already had a buyer; and the builder's profit
 came mainly from constructing the building itself.
 By as industrial capitalism changed, so too did the system.
 Increasingly, building was done on a large scale; builders speculated and
 built houses for market; financing was through credit; and the main source
 of profit became appreciated land rent, rather than profit on building
 the house itself.
 Also, Marx's comment about risking other people's capital implies that
 leverage was also becoming common.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The features of this new system are recognizable today, but with a scale
 and complexity that might shock even Marx.
 The U.S.
 is perhaps the best example of this system's extensive logic.
 Although small scale, custom, owner-contracted building is still common,
 large corporate builders increasingly dominate the U.S.
 housing market 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "wissoker2016putting"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
by no means universal, the system has become global, with the U.S.
 being perhaps the most .
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In late eighteenth-century Britain, land-rent still had feudal vestiges.
 Market forces were beginning to penetrate the realm of land ownership and
 rent, but Britain's landed aristocracy still owned the preponderance of
 land and collected rent from tenant farmers.
 It is therefore unsurprising that David Ricardo's 
\emph on
Principles of Political Economy and Taxation
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
before "[1817]"
key "ricardo1821onthe"

\end_inset

, justly famous for its pioneering work on land rent, mainly deals with
 agrarian land rent.
 But, as the passage above from Marx attests, by the mid-eighteenth century
 this had changed, and an urban land nexus involving land rent, credit,
 speculative investment, and concentration of capital was taking shape.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Urban land nexus
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 here refers to a varying set of social, economic, political, and institutional
 relations combined in particular places and times and that together create
 a particular dynamic of urbanization and construction, destruction, and
 use of the built environment.
 This dynamic, in turn, both affects and is affected by the larger set of
 relations that constitute what is commonly called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

macroeconomy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and, more generally, the social formation of which the urban land nexus
 is part.
 Allen Scott, I believe, first used the term in his book, 
\emph on
The Urban Land Nexus and the State
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
after "first published in 1980"
key "scott2013theurban"

\end_inset

.
 Interestingly, this seminal book largely ignores many things Marx mentions:
 concentration of capital, credit, finance, money, and speculation; none
 of these terms even appear in the book's index.
 The book also treats the urban land nexus as a rather fixed and universal
 feature of capitalism.
 Compared to this, my usage is more fluid in the sense that the urban land
 nexus differs over space and time within varieties of capitalism; my usage
 also sees money, monetary systems, finance capital, the role of speculation,
 etc.
 as intrinsic elements of the urban land nexus.
 In this sense, my usage comes close to what 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "haila2016urbanland"

\end_inset

calls 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

land regimes,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 except that she considers capitalism as a regime in itself, while I use
 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

urban land nexus
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to denote something that takes varied form within capitalism.
 Also see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "theurillat2015thereal"

\end_inset

 for a similar concept, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

real estate systems.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Again, my usage is less taxonomic and more concerned with developing theories
 and methods for identifying the dynamics associated with different systems.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

